Name: Academy Walk
Description: A nice walk around Fitzroy on Nicholson St, Gertrude St, Brunswick St and Johnston St.
Special_Content: Melbourne was the capital city of Australia for 26 years between 1901 and 1927 before the capital shifted to Canberra

Name: Kororoit Creek Trail
Description: Explore nature in the suburbs along the Kororoit Creek trail between Selwyn Park, Albion and Buckingham Reserve, Sunshine West on this 10km return walk.
Special_Content: Melbourne has the largest tram system outside of Europe, and the fourth largest in the world overall

Name: Pipemakers Park
Address: 2 Van Ness Avenue, Maribyrnong VIC 3032, Australia
Description: An unexpected gem in the city, this easy walk takes you along the Maribyrnong river, around a small lake and new wetlands, finishing among the wonderful gardens of Pipemakers Park.
Special_Content: Melbourne was originally named Batmania

Name: Zevenboom Lane
Description: This precinct near 'Little Lon' is a great place to start our street art tour proper. Consider this alley cat your guide?
Special_Content: The first ever set of traffic lights in Australia was installed in Melbourne

Name: Oh Donald!
Description: Sign of the times ... You may need a drink after seeing Trump sans clothes, so luckily there are some great bars along here as well as art works!
Special_Content: Until the year 1966 pubs in Melbourne closed at 6:00pm

Name: Detective stories
Description: There's a series of images here that tell a story about the man in the suit. What's this guy up to?
Special_Content: Melbourne has the highest number of restaurants and cafes per number of people than any other city in the world!

Name: Robot man on Warburton
Description: Looks like the robot man has made friends with the weird creatures to his left. It seems robots need friends too.
Special_Content: According to the Crimes Act of 1958, if you meet up with a Pirate in Melbourne, you must not trade with them…

Name: Rankins Lane
Description: Is that Toucan holding a spray can? Wander further along Rankins for more great finds plus an amazing green wall.
Special_Content: Melbourne is home to the highest Italian and Greek populations in the world outside their own countries

Name: Smell the art ...
Description: You may interrupt some live spray painting on Union Lane if you're lucky! Otherwise come and see what you can find - these walls are an ever-changing canvas.
Special_Content: In 1856, Melbourne workers successfully campaigned for the world's first 8-hour work day. All the rest of us are still thankful today!

Name: Mermans?
Description: If you have time, take a little detour down Carson Place; Ttere some moody pieces along here.
Special_Content: As of the year 2013, around 38% of Melbourne's residents were born overseas

Name: A warning
Description: Head down Howey Place and left into Presgrave - before all the lovely artworks and messages for the future are papered over?
Special_Content: A person who lives in or comes from Melbourne is called a Melbournian

Name: Coffee and crowds
Description: Degraves has to be the ultimate coffee stop on your street art tour. You may see plenty of others hunting for art here.
Special_Content: Melbourne is known for its unpredictable weather, and it's often possible to experience four seasons in one day

Name: Hosier Lane
Description: Hosier Lane is the Grandaddy of laneway art commissions in Melbourne and is arguably where the city's street art reputation was honed. It's saturated with colourful creations.
Special_Content: The maximum temperature every recorded in Melbourne was 46.4 degrees Celsius (115.5 degrees Fahrenheit) in 2009, while the minimum was -2.8 degrees Celsius (28.9 degrees Fahrenheit) all the way back in 1869

Name: Side step
Description: Take a left at Rutledge Lane where there are lots of interesting things to see. Not sure about this one though!
Special_Content: Melbourne holds the world record for highest attendance at a cricket match, with a total of 90,800 spectactors back in 1961

Name: Protest (in crochet)
Description: Hosier Lane attracts many artists who have something to say so keep your eyes wide and your heart open.
Special_Content: Major streets in Melbourne are 99ft wide. This was so a 16-horse carriage could do a U-turn.

Name: Food city?
Description: Apparently not all the well-known chefs rendered here are popular with Melbourne's fastidious palates.
Special_Content: Melbourne’s Chinatown is the oldest Chinatown in the Southern Hemisphere

Name: Great Scott! ACDC Lane
Description: Now here's the whole reason we decided to update our street art route! ACDC Lane is unmissable if you truly want to understand this city, its love of live music and of art.
Special_Content: Melbourne is the city with the most cafes per capita

Name: More than music
Description: Home to the much-loved Cherry Bar and a holy site for ACDC fans, yes. But there is more to love here if you care to look.
Special_Content: There are wild penguins in Melbourne!

Name: RIP Malcolm
Description: Did we mention ACDC?
Special_Content: Coffees have different names in Melbourne

Name: Tattoo where the (art) is
Description: Down on Duckboard Place you'll see what looks like a giant love letter to Melbourne, but there's also a reminder about the forgotten people in our city and everywhere.
Special_Content: St Paul’s Cathedral is made of two different types of stones

Name: Architectural Fragment
Description: Petrus Spronk 1992 sculpture is beloved by Melbourne's skateboard riders. It is also a fun piece of post-modernism quoting the neo-classical facade of the State Library.
Special_Content: “Under the clocks” is a traditional meeting place in Melbourne

Name: La Trobe
Description: Governor La Trobe by Peter Corlett, 2006. This is the only Peter Corlett sculpture on this walk but he has may more around Melbourne, its suburbs and the rest of the world.
Special_Content: You can find flashing lights embedded in the footpath in Melbourne

Name: The Public Purse
Address: Elizabeth St & Bourke St, Melbourne VIC 3000
Description: In 1994, the City of Melbourne added what was described in the design brief as “unique and distinctive forms of street seating” in the streets, The Public Purse was one of them.
Special_Content: The world’s first feature film was made in Melbourne

Name: Three Businessmen
Description: These figures by Alison Weaver and Paul Quinn were installed in Swanston St. the first public sculpture in Melbourne since Vault was removed from the City Square in 1981
Special_Content: Melbourne was the first city outside of Europe and North America to host the Olympic games

Name: Time and Tide
Description: Akio Makigawa (born Japan 1948 - died in Perth 1999) has public sculptures in most Australian capital cities and several more in Melbourne.
Special_Content: The black box (for planes) was invented in Melbourne

Name: Burke and Wills Monument
Description: This is the fourth location for that this monument has stood in Melbourne since 1865. It was originally cast in Charles Summers studio in Collins St. now the location of Burlington Chambers
Special_Content: Melbourne’s tram system is the largest in the world

Name: Larry La Trobe
Description: Pam Irving’s bronze dog, “Larry La Trobe” was install in 1993 and stolen in 1995. The current sculpture a new edition cast from the original mould.
Special_Content: Lonely Planet’s headquarters are in Melbourne

Name: Warin
Address: Tennis Centre Access Rd, Melbourne VIC 3004
Description: The wooden wombat, “Warin” was carved in situ in 2002 by Des McKenna. Another one for children to climb on.
Special_Content: Melbourne was awarded “most liveable city in the world” for seven years in a row

Name: Beyond the Ocean of Existence
Description: Loretta Quinn is the brother of Paul Quinn one of the sculptors of The Three Businessmen. Nearby there are painted pole by indigenous artists, Maree Clarke and Sonja Hodge
Special_Content: Melbourne was the capital city of Australia for 26 years between 1901 and 1927 before the capital shifted to Canberra

Name: 3 Mice
Description: Along with all the aerosol art there are some unofficial street art sculptures in this lane. You will have to look carefully to find them.
Special_Content: Melbourne has the largest tram system outside of Europe, and the fourth largest in the world overall

Name: Matthew Flinders Memorial
Description: The sculptor Charles Web Gilbert, like to do everything himself, from the modelling to the casting of the sculptures.
Special_Content: Melbourne was originally named Batmania

Name: Forward Surge
Description: Installed in 1981 this modern fits perfectly into the curved architecture of the Arts Centre and Hamer Hall. The curves also delight children who try to climb them.
Special_Content: The first ever set of traffic lights in Australia was installed in Melbourne

Name: Edward VII Memorial
Description: The sculptor Bertram Mackennal was born in Fitzroy but became Australia's first international art star.
Special_Content: Until the year 1966 pubs in Melbourne closed at 6:00pm

Name: Vault, Ron Robertson-Swann
Description: In 1980 this sculpture was in the City Square and Melbourne was divided by the controversy over this sculpture. In 1981 it was moved to Batman Park by the Yarra River.
Special_Content: Melbourne has the highest number of restaurants and cafes per number of people than any other city in the world!

Name: Royal Exhibition Building
Description: The Royal Exhibition Building is a World Heritage-listed building in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia, built in 1879–1880 as part of the international exhibition movement, which presented over 50 exhibitions between 1851 and 1915 around the globe.
Special_Content: According to the Crimes Act of 1958, if you meet up with a Pirate in Melbourne, you must not trade with them…

Name: Manchester Unity Building
Description: The Manchester Unity Building is an Art Deco Gothic inspired office and retail building in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia, constructed in 1931–32 for the Manchester Unity Independent Order of Oddfellows.
Special_Content: Melbourne is home to the highest Italian and Greek populations in the world outside their own countries

Name: Melbourne Town Hall
Description: Melbourne Town Hall is the central city town hall of Melbourne, Victoria, Australia, and is a historic building in the state of Victoria since 1867.
Special_Content: In 1856, Melbourne workers successfully campaigned for the world's first 8-hour work day. All the rest of us are still thankful today!

Name: Old Treasury Building
Description: The Old Treasury Building on Spring Street in Melbourne, built 1858-62 as a home for the Treasury Department of the Government of Victoria as well as the Governor In Council, now houses a range of functions, including a museum of Melbourne history, known as Old Treasury Building Museum.
Special_Content: As of the year 2013, around 38% of Melbourne's residents were born overseas

Name: Flinders Street Railway Station
Description: Flinders Street railway station is located on the corner of Flinders and Swanston streets in the central business district of Melbourne, Victoria, Australia. Opened in 1854, the historic station serves the entire metropolitan rail network, as well as some country services to eastern Victoria.
Special_Content: A person who lives in or comes from Melbourne is called a Melbournian

Name: State Library Victoria
Description: The State Library Victoria is the state library of the Australian state of Victoria. Located in Melbourne, it was established in 1854 as the Melbourne Public Library, making it Australia's oldest public library and one of the first free libraries in the world.
Special_Content: Melbourne is known for its unpredictable weather, and it's often possible to experience four seasons in one day

Name: Government House
Description: Government House is the official residence of the governor of Victoria, currently Linda Dessau. It is located in Kings Domain, Melbourne, next to the Royal Botanic Gardens. Government House was opened in 1876, on land that had originally been set aside in 1841.
Special_Content: The maximum temperature every recorded in Melbourne was 46.4 degrees Celsius (115.5 degrees Fahrenheit) in 2009, while the minimum was -2.8 degrees Celsius (28.9 degrees Fahrenheit) all the way back in 1869

Name: The ANZ Banking Museum
Description: Museum in the City of Melbourne, Victoria
Special_Content: Melbourne holds the world record for highest attendance at a cricket match, with a total of 90,800 spectactors back in 1961

Name: Victoria Barracks
Description: Located on St Kilda Road in Melbourne, Australia, Victoria Barracks Melbourne is architecturally and historically significant. It is one of the most impressive 19th century government buildings in Victoria, Australia.
Special_Content: Major streets in Melbourne are 99ft wide. This was so a 16-horse carriage could do a U-turn.

Name: St Francis’ Church
Description: St Francis' Church on the corner of Lonsdale Street and Elizabeth Street, is the oldest Catholic church in Victoria, Australia. The main body of the church is one of very few buildings in central Melbourne which was built before the Victorian gold rush of 1851.
Special_Content: Melbourne’s Chinatown is the oldest Chinatown in the Southern Hemisphere
